      {
        "id": "b93840cd7daf1812961395d1ae754c4c74bff4a6",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 1,
          "name": "Andrew Grimberg",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "agrimberg@linuxfoundation.org",
          "username": "agrimberg"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2017-11-21 20:36:10.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1\n\nI'm seeing an awful lot of code duplication that is unneeded here. Instead of creating all new projects with all the same jobs and the only difference being the stream name also being in the project so you end up with ${project}-${stream}-${job_template} where the stream ends up being duplicated, it's better to just add an additional stream to the base project. Then you don't end up duplicating your stream name in the job name!",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "0fce10059c9ae80e19ed513bf9f0c0b1919b6aa0",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 481,
          "name": "Jessica Wagantall",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jwagantall@linuxfoundation.org",
          "username": "jwagantall"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2017-11-21 20:38:07.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nAgree with Andy... This is a simpler solution:\nhttps://gerrit.onap.org/r/#/c/24645/",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "e6c55b0eb33af296fb4848c9006a974edd7bc5be",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 57,
          "name": "Pamela Dragosh",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "pd1248@att.com",
          "username": "pdragosh"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2017-11-21 21:09:23.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI understand that. But i need to NOT run sonar jobs for the amsterdam branch. Otherwise they just run over each other depending on the branch. We won't be fixing sonar issues for Amsterdam as i understand it. If there is another solution I'd like to know.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "841036ebdcfdcb8dec6db09e62b4fab253847070",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 1,
          "name": "Andrew Grimberg",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "agrimberg@linuxfoundation.org",
          "username": "agrimberg"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2017-11-21 21:40:13.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> I understand that. But i need to NOT run sonar jobs for the\n > amsterdam branch. Otherwise they just run over each other depending\n > on the branch. We won't be fixing sonar issues for Amsterdam as i\n > understand it. If there is another solution I'd like to know.\n\nThen instead of having a project that lists out all of the other jobs, have two smaller defined projects, one \"with-sonar\" one \"without-sonar\" and only have the daily job listed in those with the needed streams. Then your base project would have all the streams, but no daily job.\n\nMy problem is that there is an extremely large amount of duplicated code here when there doesn't need to be.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
